        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>H.S. Henry &#38; Son&#44;<lb/>
                Box 3144&#44; P.O.<lb/>
                CABLE ADDRESS&#45;&#45;KENRY&#44; NEW YORK.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>48 Exchange Place&#44;<lb/>
                New York&#44; 5 Sept. 1884<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> S. Morais<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I am in receipt of your favor of 4 Inst<lb/> and notice all your remarks in reply to mine of the<lb/> 29 Ult. &#32;  I can only regret that spite&#91;&#63;&#93; of the<lb/> interest evidently taken in the affairs of the Colony<lb/> at Vineland&#44; so little to likely to result of benefit to<lb/> our poor brethren there. &#32; From the action of Mr.<lb/> D. Sulzberger in withdrawing promises made in behalf<lb/> of the family Bessman&#44; because he understood that<lb/> some people from New York were visiting the colony. I<lb/> should imagine that you thought us able to respond to<lb/> every kind of call&#44; irrespective of what I wrote to you<lb/> as to our pecuniary condition.  I can conscientiously<lb/> say on behalf of myself and colleagues&#44; that we&#91;&#63;&#93; never<lb/> made a promise to any poor colonist that we did not<lb/> carry it out&#44; and if the poor Bessmans are to be<lb/> deprived of your aid and bounty on any grounds other<lb/> than their own demerits&#44; I consider it unjust and<lb/> cruel in the extreme. In New York&#44; we are apt to<lb/> do our charity first&#44; and think of it afterwards&#8212;it is<lb/> the reverse of charity&#44; to promise a poor man something<lb/> and then&#44; because we fancy somebody else will find<lb/> the money&#44; refuse to extend the necessary aid ourselves.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have not seen any of the Larden&#91;&#63;&#93; gentleman you<lb/> mention&#8212;my time being too much occupied to enable<lb/> me to go with them to Vineland at such short notice&#44;<lb/> and their time being really too much circumscribed<lb/> to permit of their meeting me&#44; as I believe they desire<lb/> to do. &#32; They were very favorably impressed&#44; I<lb/> understand with what they said at Vineland&#44; and<lb/> consider it much more likely to prosper than any<lb/> other Colony they visited. &#32; I can assure you<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>that there is no idea about abandoning the Colony or<lb/> allowing it to disperse&#44; nor do I see any reason<lb/> for such an eventuality. No measures are<lb/> necessary to this end&#44; beyond some further money<lb/> contributions which will be forthcoming doubtless<lb/> when their necessity is made apparent&#44; and a<lb/> building up of some other &#91;&#63;&#93; at the Colony<lb/> which we have now some chance to secure.<lb/></p>
            <p>While we shal be grateful for the aid of our brethren<lb/> in Philadelphia&#44; we do not rely on them at all<lb/> as past experience tells us that it is a case of<lb/>&#34;much cry and little wool.&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>I close the correspondence with a hope that<lb/> you may still find it convenient to meet me when<lb/> I next go to Vineland&#8212;of which I &#91;&#63;&#93;  inform you<lb/> and I am&#32; Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours faithfully<lb/>
                HS Henry<lb/></p>
        </body>
